# Rule: MediatR and controller boundaries

CQRS flows go through **MediatR**: each use case is a **Command** or **Query** with a matching handler (names align with `.cursor/rules/cqrs-project-structure.mdc`: `*Command`/`*CommandHandler`, `*Query`/`*QueryHandler`).

### Commands & queries in the **boundary** assembly

Often a dedicated **Contracts** (or similarly named) project holds **both** HTTP/OpenAPI-facing shapes **and** `IRequest` / `IRequest<T>` messages: one type per use case, consumed by Endpoint (`[FromBody]`, route/query binding) **`mediator.Send`**, and by Application **handlers** — no duplicate message type alongside a separate `*Request` unless your team deliberately splits transport from application messaging.

Response models (`*Dto`, `*Response`) usually live in that same boundary layer beside the slice.

## Controllers (Api / EndPoint)

- Controllers **map HTTP only**. Do not embed use-case orchestration or persistence in actions beyond binding and `Send`.
- **Forbidden in controllers:** EF `DbContext`, ORM fluent API usage, persistence interfaces used for querying/saving, raw data-access calls, `SaveChanges` orchestration — those belong behind MediatR handlers (or infra used by handlers).

*(Adjust the forbidden list if you use another stack; the invariant is **no persistence in controllers**.)*

### Route + body

When part of the state comes from the path and part from JSON, deserialize the body into your message type then **merge route values once** (e.g. `command with { Id = routeId }`) before `Send` — keeps a single canonical message shape for handlers.

## Where persistence belongs

Handlers in Application (or infrastructure adapters invoked by handlers) own data access—not controllers.

## Examples (generic)

```csharp
// ✅ GOOD — message from boundary assembly as body + Send (when your architecture allows it)
public async Task<IActionResult> Create([FromBody] SubmitEnvelopeCommand command, CancellationToken ct)
{
    var id = await mediator.Send(command, ct);
    return Created($"{Request.Path}/{id}", value: id);
}

// ✅ GOOD — parameterless query
public async Task<IActionResult> ListMine(CancellationToken ct)
{
    var items = await mediator.Send(new ListMyItemsQuery(), ct);
    return Ok(items);
}
```

```csharp
// ❌ BAD — querying EF (or equivalent) directly in an action
var rows = await dbContext.Items.Where(...).ToListAsync(ct);
```

FluentValidation may live at Endpoint (on the boundary types) or in the MediatR pipeline; DB access stays in handlers regardless.

## Typical controller dependencies

`IMediator`, HTTP-only primitives (routing, authorization, **optional** “current user” / correlation services), validators—**not** types whose job is querying or updating persistent store.
